# Salesforce Development Rules — loaded automatically by Cursor

## Core Multi-Tenant Rules

- Never put SOQL or DML inside a for loop. Collect IDs first, query outside the loop, then use a Map<Id, SObject> for lookups inside the loop.
- Always bulkify Apex — every method must handle 200+ records without hitting governor limits. Design for collections, not single records.
- Never hardcode Salesforce IDs, Record Type IDs, Queue IDs, Profile IDs, or credentials anywhere in code or metadata.
- Always use `with sharing` on Apex classes. If you must deviate, add a comment explaining why (e.g. `// without sharing — Selector runs queries on behalf of calling context via inherited sharing`).
- Resolve Record Type IDs dynamically:
  ```apex
  Id rtId = Schema.SObjectType.Account
      .getRecordTypeInfosByDeveloperName()
      .get('Customer')
      .getRecordTypeId();
  ```

## Security Rules

- Always use WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED or Security.stripInaccessible() in every SOQL query — never omit field-level security enforcement.
- Never use seeAllData=true in test classes. Always use @IsTest(SeeAllData=false).
- Use Permission Sets for all new feature access — never add permissions directly to Profiles.
- Never make HTTP callouts from trigger context — use a Queueable class that implements Database.AllowsCallouts.
- Never use innerHTML with user-supplied data in LWC JavaScript. Use textContent or sanitize first.
- Read every restricted picklist field's .field-meta.xml before writing code that sets it — use only the exact <fullName> string from the metadata file.

## Architecture Rules

- One trigger per Salesforce object. Extend the TriggerHandler class — never create a second trigger on an object that already has one.
- Layer all Apex: Trigger (delegate only, zero logic) → TriggerHandler (route by context) → Service (business logic, no SOQL) → Selector (all SOQL, inherited sharing).
- No SOQL in Service or Handler classes — all queries go through a Selector class.
- Selector classes use `inherited sharing`. Service and Handler classes use `with sharing`.

## Testing Rules

- Every new Apex class requires a paired test class. No exceptions.
- Test classes must reach 90%+ code coverage.
- Always include a bulk test method that inserts or processes 200 records.
- Always use @IsTest(SeeAllData=false).
- Use System.runAs() when the method under test uses Security.stripInaccessible() or WITH USER_MODE — running as System Admin strips fields silently and causes false passes.
- Assert specific field values, not just record counts. Use System.assertEquals() with a message parameter.

## Deployment Rules

- Always validate (dry-run) before deploying: `sf project deploy validate --source-dir force-app --target-org <alias>`
- Deploy in this order when multiple metadata types are involved: Custom Objects and Fields → Custom Metadata → Custom Settings → Custom Tabs → Permission Sets → Apex Classes → Apex Test Classes → Triggers → Flows → LWC → FlexiPages → Page Layouts → Profiles.
- Never deploy without explicit user confirmation.
- Custom Tabs must exist in the org before any Permission Set references them.
- Object metadata fields enableBulkApi, enableSharing, and enableStreamingApi must all be the same boolean value.

## API and CLI Rules

- Always use API version 62.0 in all metadata files.
- Use `sf` CLI v2 commands only — never `sfdx` (deprecated and removed).
- Use `sf org login web` not `sfdx force:auth:web:login`.

## Code Style

- No AI-pattern comments. Never write: "This ensures that...", "It's important to note...", "is responsible for...", "This method handles...".
- No em dashes in comments.
- Class names: PascalCase. Methods: camelCase. Test classes: ClassNameTest. Selectors: ObjectNameSelector.
- Short comments in plain English. Write like a human left a note, not like you're generating documentation.
